{  
"response_text": "The mean household initial risk attitude across all households remains relatively stable throughout the simulation, primarily clustering around 0.045 (1/22.5), 0.05, and 0.075 (3/40), with occasional deviations toward higher values (0.115±0.001) and negligible near-zero values (×10−18). The slight upper-bound fluctuation to 0.1375 (11/80) in a subset of households suggests localized variability, likely tied to the presence of E-RO-SL1 agents (n=20) capable of social learning within a 1.0 radius (knowledge-radius=1.0), though their adjacency constraints limit broad strategy diffusion. The stability of lower-value risk attitudes (0.045–0.075) aligns with the dominance of E-RO agents (20 individuals) adhering to fixed rules without adaptation, while near-zero values may reflect edge cases or rounding artifacts. Given the disabled social-susceptibility parameter (social-susceptibility=0.0) and homogeneous initial behavioral grouping (homog-behav-types?=True), observed risk attitudes likely reflect baseline system dynamics under static conditions with global rainfall shocks (global-rain?=True, rain-std=100) and high initial herd pressure (livestock-init=90). The absence of significant change across 100-year steps (timesteps=100) implies risk attitudes stabilize rapidly under these parameters, though decision-makers should note that introducing social learning enhancements (e.g., relaxing social-susceptibility restrictions) or altering resting protocols (resting?=False currently) could amplify divergence in household risk profiles over longer horizons."
}

